==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Martin
<hw>Mar"tin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Stone Working)</fld>
<ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety> <def>A perforated stone-faced runner for
grinding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Martin
<hw>Mar"tin</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>martin</ets>, from the
proper name <ets>Martin</ets>. Cf. <er>Martlet</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>One of several species of swallows, usually
having the tail less deeply forked than the tail of the common
swallows.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>marten</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The American <stype>purple martin</stype>, or <stype>bee
martin</stype> (<spn>Progne subis</spn> or <spn>Progne purpurea</spn>),
and the European <stype>house martin</stype>, or <stype>window
martin</stype> (<spn>Hirundo urbica</spn> or <spn>Chelidon
urbica</spn>), are the best known species.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bank martin</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The bank
swallow</cd>. See under <er>Bank</er>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The fairy
martin. See under <er>Fairy</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Bee martin</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The purple martin</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>The
kingbird.</cd> -- <col><b>Sand martin</b></col>, <cd>the bank
swallow.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Martinet</ent>⟦br⟧
